Backing up a little further, those of us who are involved with the Big Brothers Big Sisters of MS program, mentoring children at Sunnybrook Children's home had a meeting during lunch yesterday with Ms. Lewis & Ms. Coalter about the issues of the foster care program in MS as well as the fact that so many of us have lost our kids: Allison, Susie, Edmund, Carrie, Chris all are on their 2nd child, & thats 5 out of 9 of us that are involved with the program.

When Sunnybrook takes the kids somewhere else be it a psych hospital, another children's home, whatever they won't tell us where anything about what happened to them. I mean once you've spent 5 or 6 Wednesdays with your child, you get attached and then one day you come and they're gone.. its horrible. I'm one of the lucky ones so far, I still have my original "little" as does Leigh, Melanie, and Ashley. I can't imagine what I would do if she was to be taken away. 
     
That's another thing that infuriates me about this state... MS has one of the worst foster care programs. So, so many of these kids get lost in the system. There are too many children & not enough case workers, most of the case workers are dealing with up to 40 different cases which is ridiculous.

It makes me so angry when I know of something that I can't make better. We want the kids to know that we'll be there for them, but Sunnybrook won't allow us to bring them anything including food or candy, we can't take pictures with them, we aren't suppose to hug them, (though we do that anyway) and our time with them is only 45 minutes a week which is definitely not enough time to really help them study for a test or whatever. 

Many of us have tried to request another day to come and tutor, but their schedule at Sunnybrook is so tight that they won't allow it. The environment at the cottages that they live in is not a desirable learning environment and their cottage parents usually aren't educated enough to help them with their homework, and if they are, they can't give individual help because there are 10 girls living in a cabin.

I don't know what I'm going to do at the end of the school year when the program is over. Not knowing what's going to happen to my "little" bothers me, and I want to be able to maintain contact with her, to let her know that I care about her.

But, still I just got to school after having an 8:30 appt at the ENT to look at my CT scan results that I ended up having to get yesterday. I've had a CT before, but I didn't remember having to lay on my stomach with all my weight pressing on my chin.. at least it wasn't a MRI. I get so claustrophobic and the fact that they strap your head down and that it takes 45 mins doesn't help things. The CT scan results didn't show much. Oh, well I guess I make up for the rest of my family since none of them have chronic med problems...
